Restoring after the fuckup
==========================

I hope i'm not the only one who completely deleted her `$HOME` by mistake.  
Well, I _know_ I'm not the only one, this is from the UNIX-HATERS Handbook:

> Unix aficionados accept occasional file deletion as normal. For example,
> consider following excerpt from the `comp.unix.questions` FAQ:
> > 
> > 6) How do I “undelete” a file?
> >
> > Someday, you are going to accidentally type something like:
> > 
> > `% rm * .foo`
> > 
> > and find you just deleted `“*”` instead of `“*.foo”`. Consider it a
> > rite of passage.
> > 
> > Of course, any decent systems administrator should be doing
> > regular backups. Check with your sysadmin to see if a recent
> > backup copy of your file is available.
> > 
> “A rite of passage”? In no other industry could a manufacturer take such a
> cavalier attitude toward a faulty product. “But your honor, the exploding
> gas tank was just a rite of passage.” “Ladies and gentlemen of the jury, we
> will prove that the damage caused by the failure of the safety catch on our
> chainsaw was just a rite of passage for its users.” “May it please the court,
> we will show that getting bilked of their life savings by Mr. Keating was
> just a rite of passage for those retirees.” Right.

Well, in my case it's a little different. I was doing some cleanup with this
handy function I made some time ago:  

`uprm () { cd .. && rm -rf "$OLDPWD" ; }`

Cool, isn't it? What could go wrong with it?  

I did `ls otherdir` and got no result, then I typed `uprm` thinking I was in
`otherdir`... and of course I got this error message:  

`Cannot remove /home/izabera : Permission denied`  

Sudden realization. Horror. Tears.  
My IRC friends are still laughing. :(  

I just deleted all my local files, my documents, my git trees, my notporn
directory... Everything.  

Ok, most of the documents are rsynced on my vps too, and I can clone again my
git trees from various remotes. I lost my uncommitted work, but that wasn't
much anyway.  

And this is what `uprm` looks like right now:

```bash
uprm () {  
  if [ "${PWD%/*}" = /home ] ; then  
    echo Nope.  
    return 1  
  else  
    cd .. && rm -rf "$OLDPWD"  
  fi  
}
```

Thanks to `#bash` :P

